Extra ordinary times call for extra ordinary resourcefulness, actions and decisions. Thankfully, the hard actions demanded by the unique circumstances of the moment come during the era of devolution, when priority setting, decision-making and resource utilisation has since been devolved to various action centres at the devolved units.
With the enormous resources and functions that have since been devolved to action stations on the sub-national levels of government, there exists considerable leadership capacity, resources and institutional assets to bring to bear to the emergency health requirement to set up extra facilities to enable school-entry. 
These include the National Government Constituency Development Fund (NG-CDF). Leadership and institutions at the local level should be mobilised to play a role and offload the burden of emergency response from school managers.
Non-state actors involved in education delivery, including faith-based institutions, philanthropists and development partners should offer a helping hand on how to deliver extra physical facilities and human resources in an emergency situation visited on the public education sector by the covid-19 pandemic.
Procurement procedures



